Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Equity Bank, Standard of Kenya Move

-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 
2011-03-30T12:49:21Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-30/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-equity-bank-standard-of-kenya-move.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index climbed
for an eighth day, adding 0.2 percent to 1,998.67 by the 1:30
p.m. close in Port Louis.  Kenya ’s All-Share Index increased 0.1 percent to 72.05 by
the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi, paring its drop this year to 7.3
percent. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index lost 0.4
percent to 24,656.66 at 1:34 p.m. in Lagos, taking its retreat
in 2011 to 0.5 percent, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  rallied 1 percent to
867.17 by 2:35 p.m. in Windhoek, heading for a three-week high.
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index fell 0.6 percent to
1,062.92 by 12:35 p.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Equity Bank Ltd. (EQBNK)   added 25 cents, or 1 percent,
to 25 shillings, the highest since March 25. Kenya’s biggest
lender by market value plans to open five branches in Rwanda
and three in Tanzania, Chief Executive Officer James Mwangi
said in Nairobi today. Equity Bank will start operating in
Rwanda in April and in Tanzania in May, he said.  Standard Group Ltd. (STNG)   jumped 1.25 shillings, or 3.3
percent, to 39.25 shillings, the highest in more than a week.
Kenya’s second-biggest media company said it would redeem
preference shares at 10 shillings each, according to an e-mailed
statement from the  Nairobi Stock Exchange .  To contact the reporter on this story:
Eric Ombok in Nairobi at 
 eombok@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Gavin Serkin at 
 gserkin@bloomberg.net  